{Partner opened and you hold a powerhouse — twenty points, a strong diamond suit, and every control you could want — so you announce the strength at once with a jump shift and take charge.
[BID 1C] Partner opens 1\C, a normal opening promising at least three clubs and asking you to describe.
[BID 2D] You jump-shift to 2\D, a Soloway jump — game-forcing with slam interest, showing a strong diamond suit and seven controls: three aces and a king, well past the four-plus the bid promises.
[BID 2N] Partner bids an artificial 2NT, a waiting call that shows no clear fit for your diamonds and no extra shape to describe.
[BID 4N] With no fit uncovered you offer 4\N as a quantitative raise, inviting slam if partner has anything beyond a bare minimum.
[show NESW]Partner had nothing to spare and passed, so four notrump was the right ceiling and it rolled home for eleven tricks. Quantitative four notrump lets the big hand ask the question without committing past game, and here the honest minimum opposite made stopping exactly right.}
